00:20.238 --> 00:23.601
Well, we don't have to cover everything.

00:23.741 --> 00:26.643
I've got a lot of what I told you about myself in there.

00:27.224 --> 00:30.707
I mean, there was a lot of personal stuff that I don't think we have to go over there.

00:30.827 --> 00:33.109
I am very interested in

00:33.865 --> 00:35.107
You said you were in the Peace Corps?

00:35.728 --> 00:36.048
Yes.

00:36.068 --> 00:36.689
In the late 60s.

00:36.869 --> 00:43.679
And the area of Nigeria that became the Afrin seceded for a year after the Civil War began.

00:43.839 --> 00:47.925
I went to Liberia and I was there for a year and a half.

00:47.945 --> 00:50.709
Do you have your biographical background in there?

00:50.729 --> 00:52.091
You said you went to schools again?

00:52.111 --> 00:53.773
University of Redlands.

00:53.833 --> 00:58.059
Graduated from the University of Redlands.

00:58.079 --> 00:58.620
What year was that?

00:58.640 --> 00:58.920
1964.

00:58.940 --> 00:59.461
1964.

00:59.501 --> 01:02.185
You're studying at the United Nations.

01:02.536 --> 01:11.607
program at Drew University in Madison, New Jersey.

01:12.528 --> 01:21.619
Western State, I went to UCLA Law School for two years, and then was out for six years, that was when I was in the Peace Corps, and I finished up at Western State University.

01:25.283 --> 01:31.851
And then just tell me, you've been here in Sacramento, I think you said 16 years, you worked for the

01:32.455 --> 01:35.418
I was a lawyer for the legislature for a couple of years.

01:36.099 --> 01:41.205
I've been an administrative law judge for nine years.

01:41.225 --> 01:50.876
I hear and decide cases involving unemployment matters, disability matters, some tax matters within the lawyers.

01:50.896 --> 01:52.037
So you draw a state salary?

01:52.338 --> 01:52.918
Yes, I do.

01:52.938 --> 01:53.839
A fixed salary.

01:54.180 --> 01:55.101
Right.

01:55.942 --> 02:01.748
Which is interesting to me because your means, regardless of what they are, are not a millionaire's risk.

02:01.769 --> 02:02.209
That's right.

02:02.797 --> 02:11.569
And that is interesting, because every book collector can, anyone can collect satisfactorily at whatever level they're true.

02:11.629 --> 02:12.751
Sure, yeah.

02:12.771 --> 02:24.266
And, you know, with me, it's, it's, I sometimes used to very poor judgment in, in, in, I mean, to digress, it's an emotional experience the first time you spend a hundred dollars for a book.

02:24.827 --> 02:32.297
And it's another kind of experience the first time you spend a thousand dollars for a book, and the first time you spend, you know, significantly more than that.

02:32.547 --> 02:42.287
You keep on upping the ante, and I have found myself making decisions to buy when it really wasn't wise financially, and there's been a real struggle.

02:42.848 --> 02:47.277
Hopefully I don't do that anymore, but I've certainly done it in the past.

02:47.297 --> 02:52.007
You did say that the first collectible, per se, that you bought was after you got out of the Peace Corps.

02:52.763 --> 02:57.928
No, it was Death in the Afternoon Without a Jacket.

02:58.048 --> 02:58.348
Right.

02:59.029 --> 03:00.650
And that kind of began.

03:00.690 --> 03:06.916
Yeah, I learned that there were first editions, that people collected them, and this was a big, beautiful book, you know.

03:07.717 --> 03:12.261
And then I started going to bookstores, used bookstores and rare bookstores and talking.

03:13.162 --> 03:21.049
And in over 23 years, people who have gotten to know about me as a real serious Hemingway collector, I get 250 to 300

03:21.383 --> 03:24.448
catalogs a year from book dealers throughout the country.

03:25.289 --> 03:36.126
And the most wonderful find, which you read about in the New York Times, the way that arose, there was a book dealer in Florida who knew me as a serious Hemingway collector.

03:37.288 --> 03:49.146
And he telephoned me one day, said someone had walked into his shop and handed him, and I'll show you exactly what he was handed right now, and handed him a couple of

03:49.598 --> 03:56.164
typed it in pages and it said that it was a Hemingway short story and that his mother had typed for Hemingway in Cuba in the 30s.

03:56.224 --> 03:56.585
Wow.

03:57.626 --> 04:00.809
And the dealer sent it to me and said, is this really Hemingway?

04:02.030 --> 04:03.131
And what is it?

04:03.531 --> 04:06.214
So he was sending it to you for a consultation as much as anything else.

04:06.234 --> 04:06.815
Yes, right.

04:06.835 --> 04:12.420
What he sent me were Xerox copies of these two pages.

04:12.720 --> 04:14.001
Okay.

04:14.022 --> 04:17.665
And that is the first draft

04:17.797 --> 04:23.442
of the story of the capital of the world, Hemingway did it on his typewriter.

04:23.462 --> 04:31.830
And you know it's his because it has the characteristic spacing before as well as after the commas, and he would do that to slow himself down when he typed.

04:31.850 --> 04:37.436
The way he wrote the story, he did four type pages and 38 manuscript pages.

04:37.456 --> 04:38.817
That's the first draft of the story.

04:39.277 --> 04:47.365
The Kennedy Museum in Boston has the second two type pages and the 38 manuscript pages, and these are the first two type pages.

04:47.564 --> 04:51.267
And their story, what they have, begins right here, where this leaves on.

04:51.287 --> 04:51.668
Really?

04:51.688 --> 05:00.055
In addition, there's a complete carbon type script of the story with ink collections in Hemingway's hand on page four.

05:01.356 --> 05:08.803
And he would count the numbering in pencil on each of the pages is in his hand.

05:09.143 --> 05:13.207
He was notorious for counting his output each day.

05:13.307 --> 05:13.627
That's right.

05:13.647 --> 05:16.930
He wanted to do 600 words minimum a day, something like that.

05:17.703 --> 05:20.066
Anyway, this is what the dealer in Florida sent me.

05:20.086 --> 05:21.828
And I sent him back a letter saying, yes, it is.

05:22.509 --> 05:25.333
And this also is a pencil insert in his hand.

05:26.555 --> 05:28.257
Sure.

05:28.277 --> 05:28.697
Okay.

05:28.718 --> 05:32.002
He was a well-built baby.

05:32.663 --> 05:41.474
He was a well-built boy with very black, rather curly hair, good teeth, and a skin that his sisters envied.

05:41.715 --> 05:44.098
And he had a ready and unpuzzled smile.

05:44.679 --> 05:45.820
He was fast on his feet.

05:46.407 --> 05:47.368
and did his work well.

05:47.569 --> 05:49.331
And it goes in right there.

05:49.592 --> 05:51.234
And it says, insert page one.

05:51.254 --> 05:51.614
Yeah.

05:51.634 --> 05:55.099
And he loved his sisters who seemed beautiful and sophisticated.

05:56.421 --> 05:57.763
And then look at that, look at the comma.

05:57.823 --> 05:59.345
And that's Hemingway.

05:59.465 --> 06:00.727
That's no question.

06:00.747 --> 06:00.988
Oh, yeah.

06:01.008 --> 06:01.168
Right.

06:01.188 --> 06:01.889
That's good prose.

06:01.969 --> 06:04.613
That's not bad, is it?

06:04.633 --> 06:05.955
So what did you think when you saw this?

06:05.975 --> 06:12.464
Well, I was just astounded because, you know, Hemingway typescripts or manuscripts are all in museums.

06:13.285 --> 06:14.727
And the story that this guy...

06:15.297 --> 06:18.962
He walks into the store, and he hands this to the book dealer, and he says, this is a Hemingway.

06:18.982 --> 06:20.864
My mom talked for Hemingway, Cuba.

06:20.945 --> 06:23.628
So I wrote the dealer a letter, and I said, is there more?

06:23.909 --> 06:24.369
Yes, it is.

06:24.449 --> 06:25.130
It's the real thing.

06:25.170 --> 06:26.272
I told him what story it was.

06:26.712 --> 06:27.914
Is there more, and is it for sale?

06:28.695 --> 06:32.059
Actually, before I got the letter, I phoned him.

06:32.119 --> 06:32.700
I couldn't wait.

06:33.962 --> 06:43.915
And so then he told me what he knew about it, and he told me a price that he thought that it could be had for, because they talked about a price, because the guy wanted his son.

06:43.935 --> 06:45.237
What was the price?

06:47.242 --> 06:48.804
Well, the price was $10,000.

06:48.844 --> 06:50.646
That's not bad.

06:50.886 --> 06:52.288
No, it wasn't.

06:53.429 --> 06:57.273
But what I did is offer that, and there was no deal.

06:59.075 --> 07:01.057
But you got another dealer involved, unfortunately.

07:01.077 --> 07:05.222
Well, no, I didn't mind the dealer being involved, because I was then a collector, really.

07:07.464 --> 07:07.985
When was this?

07:08.065 --> 07:09.286
Did we say what year this was?

07:09.307 --> 07:10.628
Yeah, this was about three years ago.

07:11.068 --> 07:12.971
Okay, 1987, we'll say.

07:13.311 --> 07:13.591
Yes.

07:14.913 --> 07:15.173
Okay.

07:15.811 --> 07:18.975
Actually, I was a dealer, but he knew me as a collector.

07:19.055 --> 07:21.838
You know, I was just barely beginning in the business.

07:23.921 --> 07:25.964
So a process began then.

07:25.984 --> 07:32.712
The book dealer dealing with the owner of this material and myself in California.

07:33.273 --> 07:34.915
And I kept on asking, is there more?

07:34.935 --> 07:38.359
And it turned out there were six inscribed magazine appearances.

07:38.599 --> 07:43.405
This typescript and some wonderful photographs and a few other...

07:44.060 --> 07:52.769
things, but primarily the six inscribed, oh, a letter, a book by Martha Gelman, or a certain Y, which was inscribed.

07:55.472 --> 07:58.395
Well, we're going to talk about just whatever you're feeling.

07:58.916 --> 08:01.419
Yeah.

08:01.439 --> 08:11.529
For Phyllis Armstrong, who did most of the work with gratitude and affection, Martha Gelman, San Francisco de Paul, that's the Finca in Cuba, where, of course, Martha lived for just four years.

08:11.930 --> 08:12.891
Yeah.

08:13.371 --> 08:13.932
Mary lived

08:14.266 --> 08:21.977
Most of the time there, but... Anyway, the novel... This is A Stricken Field, a novel of today by Martha Gellhorn.

08:22.157 --> 08:23.259
Right.

08:23.279 --> 08:23.859
Okay.

08:23.879 --> 08:25.121
For the sake of the tape, yeah.

08:25.181 --> 08:25.442
Right.

08:25.462 --> 08:28.986
And this is one of the inscribed magazine appearances.

08:29.006 --> 08:30.148
Oh, that's kind of nice.

08:30.168 --> 08:32.351
This is The Spanish War by Ernest Hemingway.

08:32.531 --> 08:32.912
Right.

08:32.932 --> 08:37.318
It's to Jane Armstrong, best always Ernest Hemingway, and that signature is... Right.

08:37.438 --> 08:38.740
Absolutely.

08:39.721 --> 08:41.324
It's like looking at... Right.

08:41.864 --> 08:42.025
Right.

08:42.545 --> 08:43.767
Just to give you a real...

08:44.236 --> 08:47.639
Jane Armstrong married to Richard Armstrong.

