Phyllis typed, for whom the bell tolls.

09:09.459 --> 09:11.121
Now, I have here...

09:12.181 --> 09:13.883
This is all from the same collection?

09:14.063 --> 09:17.228
Yeah, all of this stuff virtually is from the same collection.

09:17.248 --> 09:17.788
Wow.

09:17.808 --> 09:19.270
But I got it from different places.

09:19.370 --> 09:24.417
See, I got some from the grandson of Jane, the son of Phyllis, and some later I'll get to the story.

09:24.457 --> 09:26.079
How were you beating out everybody else?

09:26.860 --> 09:30.184
How did you have an exclusive... Okay, let me just go on with the story.

09:30.204 --> 09:34.410
Okay, but this is... I'm curious to know why the JFK... It's a wonderful story involved in this.

09:34.550 --> 09:34.910
Right.

09:34.930 --> 09:35.611
How come they weren't?

09:36.332 --> 09:36.973
Right.

09:37.375 --> 09:38.577
bidding for this.

09:38.797 --> 09:39.839
Okay.

09:40.259 --> 09:41.802
We're going to finish your story and we'll get to that.

09:41.822 --> 09:43.104
Yeah.

09:43.344 --> 09:46.469
So I kept on asking, is there more?

09:46.569 --> 09:52.798
And finally, he made a list of what he had and sent it to the book dealer.

09:54.180 --> 09:58.767
And so then I made an offer for the whole thing.

09:59.007 --> 09:59.648
To the dealer?

09:59.829 --> 10:00.870
To the dealer.

10:00.910 --> 10:01.832
But I said, it's all or nothing.

10:02.012 --> 10:04.075
I don't want to negotiate individual prices.

10:04.493 --> 10:16.503
There were also a bunch of magazine clippings and news clippings from the 30s and 40s, you know, which were itemized individually, but of course didn't have any value, comparatively speaking.

10:16.523 --> 10:21.487
But in any case, I did make an offer of the whole thing because I didn't want to, you know, have to negotiate.

10:22.668 --> 10:24.070
In any case, he said yes.

10:24.930 --> 10:28.733
And so I flew back to Florida.

10:28.754 --> 10:34.078
And the book dealer and I drove 100 miles to this small Florida seacoast town.

10:34.700 --> 10:40.328
and went into this man's house and purchased this wonderful material.

10:40.348 --> 10:41.150
Let me show you.

10:41.530 --> 10:44.174
Can you tell me who the dealer is, or is that something you'd rather not say?

10:44.535 --> 10:48.020
Oh, I'd just soon not say, but I will, because he's a good friend.

10:48.441 --> 10:49.142
Well, he didn't do anything.

10:50.063 --> 10:50.524
No, no.

10:50.684 --> 10:53.148
It's Michael Slicker of Lighthouse Books in Florida.

10:53.188 --> 10:54.109
He's a good friend.

10:54.207 --> 11:00.854
And he's the best, most prominent book dealer in Florida, so it would be easy to find out.

11:01.034 --> 11:01.775
Well, I could follow him.

11:01.795 --> 11:01.955
Yeah.

11:02.236 --> 11:03.197
Oh, yeah.

11:03.357 --> 11:04.638
There's really no reason not to.

11:04.658 --> 11:06.661
I mean, there's nothing that's improper, so.

11:06.841 --> 11:07.101
No.

11:07.602 --> 11:12.247
The only thing is, if he gets Hemingway's stuff, I want him to offer it to me.

11:13.028 --> 11:13.568
You know what I mean?

11:14.129 --> 11:21.717
The point is, I'm getting this information with the idea of publishing it, so it's, you know, I mean, you're going to be interested.

11:22.017 --> 11:26.142
Introduced to a reading public here.

11:26.683 --> 11:32.090
This is perhaps one of the other wonderful things from this collection.

11:32.110 --> 11:39.719
Cosmopolitan, the story Nobody Ever Dies, was not republished in book form until the complete stories for Ernest Hemingway in 1987.

11:40.420 --> 11:41.642
What Cosmopolitan is that?

11:41.822 --> 11:43.464
It's March of 1939.

11:43.644 --> 11:46.088
I'll be looking for it.

11:46.108 --> 11:47.369
Yes, yes.

11:47.389 --> 11:51.214
But in the first three or four paragraphs, the portraits are...

11:51.532 --> 11:57.469
the porch or upper porch, from which you can see the Havana Harbor, is mentioned in the text.

