18:23.286 --> 18:24.688
Is this for sale, too, by the way?

18:26.035 --> 18:49.900
yeah yeah okay but it says by ernest hemingway key west florida u.s first serial rights only yeah um that is an old paper i i'll choose not to touch right the the first is a little rough and the last couple are rough but otherwise it's it's a wonderful condition yeah it is and this is obviously the box that probably you know the box

18:50.555 --> 18:51.115
I would say.

18:51.216 --> 18:52.597
In Spanish, you probably bought it.

18:52.797 --> 18:56.240
In Blanco, B-L-A-N-C-O.

18:56.360 --> 18:58.101
Makina de Esco by typing paper.

18:58.802 --> 19:00.403
Let me write that down.

19:00.443 --> 19:00.744
Yeah.

19:02.205 --> 19:03.366
Okay, we're back on here.

19:03.386 --> 19:06.809
Before I purchased, I wanted to verify what it was.

19:07.629 --> 19:13.574
So I wrote to Kennedy, who has another typescript of Green Hills of Africa.

19:13.655 --> 19:15.096
Explain what Kennedy is.

19:15.136 --> 19:15.216
JFK.

19:15.236 --> 19:20.140
JFK Library in Boston, Massachusetts, who has the Hemingway

19:20.474 --> 19:27.381
The conversation between Mary and Jackie Kennedy is how that happens.

19:27.921 --> 19:32.126
That's not famous, but it's nice.

19:34.568 --> 19:42.977
On January 4, 1935, Jane Armstrong had basically finished typing Green Hills of Africa in Fort Reynolds.

19:43.017 --> 19:45.159
Here's a letter that she writes.

19:46.120 --> 19:50.464
He apparently was vacationing in Arkansas.

19:50.900 --> 20:02.259
And she didn't want to send a manuscript with Harrington, who was the captain of the boat that went between Havana and Key West, because she was afraid that he might not be there.

20:02.500 --> 20:03.301
You want to read the letter?

20:03.682 --> 20:04.663
Yeah, well, I just love this.

20:04.743 --> 20:12.356
It's Habana, H-A-B-A-N-A dash, January 4th, numeral 4th, T-H, just before mail time.

20:12.637 --> 20:12.837
Right.

20:13.378 --> 20:16.283
Dear Ernest, you are far too charitable,

20:17.309 --> 20:19.334
About my solitary talent.

20:19.534 --> 20:21.259
About my solitary talent, Gash.

20:21.840 --> 20:24.947
And besides, it's languished beneath a bushel.

20:25.569 --> 20:33.608
Or have I got that next during the holidays, which snuck up like, snuck is best called, like fees in the night or something.

20:33.628 --> 20:35.132
The thing is, I'm overwhelmed.

20:35.804 --> 20:38.708
with remorse at visions of your... Maybe you can read it better.

20:38.768 --> 20:39.088
Okay.

20:39.349 --> 20:49.663
The thing is, I'm overwhelmed with remorse at visions of your face peering hopefully up at the bridge of the Cuba tomorrow, that's the name of the boat, when there isn't going to be any manuscript aboard.

20:50.003 --> 20:55.551
But then maybe you aren't back from Arkansas yet anyway, and it might get lost if you didn't claim it in person.

20:56.492 --> 21:04.022
I took you literally about it being a rough copy, and as I've galloped along, Rick has trailed me with a pencil picking up lapses.

21:04.340 --> 21:28.356
in a few instances that's her husband richard a few instances i've left wide open spaces to fill in a word it will be largely done for the boat on wednesday the ninth and the remainder to go forward at earliest possible moment which maybe i can write a more coherent note the dos passos are here to go over to the isle of pines tonight and later on down in the british west indies and this morning rick

21:28.876 --> 21:38.446
had a cordial note from Miss Kaldewaler, C-A-D-A-W-A-L-L-A-D-A-R, with the Tarplin book of Demox he'd long wanted.

21:38.466 --> 21:48.097
Unless you hear otherwise by cable, then most of the manuscript, with copy and carbon, will be confided to Captain H next Wednesday morning.

21:48.597 --> 21:56.706
Now, the manuscript and the two typescripts, one of them is in the...

21:57.682 --> 22:02.107
The Kennedy Museum in Boston.

22:03.188 --> 22:05.190
About approximately 260 pages.

22:05.430 --> 22:10.376
The missing 80 pages from that draft is with the University of Delaware Library.

22:11.777 --> 22:15.801
Now the only one with corrections in Hemingway's hand is the portion of the one at Boston.

22:16.382 --> 22:26.693
I got Xerox copies of what the Kennedy had and what the University of Delaware had before I finalized this because

22:26.960 --> 22:30.305
I wanted to make sure it was what it was.

22:31.747 --> 22:35.994
And she uses two different typefaces, and they're precisely the same.

22:36.114 --> 22:39.379
So there's this—this is nine-point type.

22:39.779 --> 22:42.664
I just saw something penciled in derriere in green ink.

22:43.204 --> 22:43.485
Yes.

22:44.106 --> 22:45.548
She said that she left some blanks.

22:45.568 --> 22:48.192
Blanks and so—that's not in Ernest's hand, though.

22:48.212 --> 22:49.294
No, it's not in Ernest's hand.

22:49.354 --> 22:51.998
I don't know whose hand that is.

22:52.078 --> 22:54.942
And there are only two or three in the whole thing.

22:55.208 --> 22:56.990
He made corrections on the other one.

22:57.210 --> 23:05.839
But basically, this letter establishes that her intention was to mail the handwritten manuscript and the two type copies back to him.

23:06.100 --> 23:07.541
Do you know what year this is going on?

23:07.561 --> 23:08.182
Yes, this is 35.

23:08.342 --> 23:08.482
Okay.

23:08.722 --> 23:09.323
Okay.

23:09.423 --> 23:10.945
Because it doesn't get the year.

23:10.965 --> 23:11.185
Right.

23:11.345 --> 23:13.027
And let me show you these other letters.

23:13.087 --> 23:13.367
Okay.

23:13.948 --> 23:18.853
So then he gets this letter, and then he sends her this telegram.

23:20.825 --> 23:23.407
Arrived yesterday meeting Harrington.

23:23.608 --> 23:26.210
That's the captain of the voltage goes back and forth.

23:26.350 --> 23:27.591
Meeting Harrington Saturday.

23:27.712 --> 23:28.793
Gratefulest, Ernest.

23:28.853 --> 23:31.495
This is January 10th, 1935.

23:32.176 --> 23:33.317
Western Union Cable.

23:33.577 --> 23:34.438
Right up.

23:34.458 --> 23:35.279
Okay.

23:35.299 --> 23:40.323
Now we've got this one.

23:40.343 --> 23:41.585
Dear Ernest.

23:41.605 --> 23:42.706
This is January 11th.

23:42.766 --> 23:43.527
Havana.

23:43.787 --> 23:44.808
She gets a telegram.

23:45.248 --> 23:46.109
She's shipping the stuff.

23:46.489 --> 23:47.710
Dear Ernest.

23:47.730 --> 23:48.271
Here it is.

23:48.571 --> 23:50.393
And however inadequate typing,

23:51.014 --> 23:55.521
And you'll notice the typeface is the same as that used in... This is important.

23:55.761 --> 23:57.283
Why do you keep pointing this out?

23:57.364 --> 23:58.145
I know why.

23:58.165 --> 24:02.832
Okay, this is nine-point type, and it's the typewriter she had at the U.S.

24:02.912 --> 24:04.154
Embassy where she worked.

24:04.875 --> 24:08.661
And also, there's elite type used in this.

24:09.582 --> 24:18.996
And at the Kennedy, what they have, of course, was done... The pages where she would change to the elite type are the same.

24:19.162 --> 24:23.608
And that's what I wanted to confirm, that this really was exactly what it was supposed to be.

24:23.648 --> 24:27.234
There's no chance that any of this could be forgeries or anything.

24:27.394 --> 24:27.654
No.

24:28.015 --> 24:30.358
Have you had any chemical stuff done on the paper?

24:30.458 --> 24:30.698
No.

24:31.099 --> 24:38.169
But, you know, looking at, I've seen what the Kennedy has, and, you know, it's just, they're both the same draft.

24:38.269 --> 24:39.631
And the provenance is excellent.

24:39.651 --> 24:40.112
Oh, yeah.

24:40.132 --> 24:40.452
Right.

24:40.893 --> 24:42.916
So here's this letter, which he actually sent it to him.

24:42.956 --> 24:43.437
Here it is.

24:43.517 --> 24:47.903
And however inadequate it typed in, when I could, I worked on my machine at the office,

24:48.203 --> 24:52.088
And for the rest of it, use this old mill, which you know so well.

24:52.468 --> 24:55.332
Now, I guess this is the one she had at home, the nine-point type.

24:55.352 --> 24:57.675
Like hunting greater kudu with a popcorn.

24:58.156 --> 25:06.026
It was a great experience watching it unfold, the vibrant Africa I knew it must be, the country you're homesick for, though you've never seen it.

25:06.486 --> 25:09.370
Not glamorous, not romantic, but so much better than that.

25:10.091 --> 25:10.431
That's excellent.

25:10.451 --> 25:15.578
The engaging personalities moving in their own rhythms, standing out in their full stature,

25:15.946 --> 25:22.516
stature and integrity of their own background, not thrown in as props to hold glory-reflecting mirrors.

25:23.477 --> 25:25.260
You forgot remarks, Rick, at this point.

25:25.681 --> 25:28.144
It wasn't Halliburton writing the story.

25:29.326 --> 25:43.708
The introspective digressions, too, are well included, particularly that one magnificent passage of the Gulf Stream soliloquy, all developed with that deceptive simplicity so devilish to achieve which has confounded even your better imitators.

25:44.195 --> 25:46.979
The things you changed your mind about are illuminating too.

25:47.580 --> 25:49.142
It's grand to have seen it in the making.

25:49.602 --> 25:58.555
Some of the construction and hyphenation left me in somewhat of a quandary because I haven't forgotten that crack you made about my having copied even your mistakes.

25:59.156 --> 26:01.439
But who am I to say when they are?

26:01.739 --> 26:09.510
If, as you suggested, you find your way clear to send the manuscript back, I'll be inexpressibly delighted to have it.

26:09.845 --> 26:16.753
but I'm not interested in knowing who might be able to dispose of it, just how many libraries have a Hemingway holograph.

26:16.773 --> 26:19.296
Best to you all from both of us.

26:19.316 --> 26:19.857
All right.

26:19.877 --> 26:21.038
These are Carvins, of course.

26:21.158 --> 26:25.964
Yeah, she kept Carvins of her own, and then she... That was dated Havana, January 11th.

26:26.144 --> 26:26.424
Right.

26:26.945 --> 26:28.206
And then here's his response.

26:28.246 --> 26:29.228
This is the letter.

26:29.848 --> 26:35.855
February 5th, 1935, Box 406, Key West, and pencil in Hemingway's hand.

26:36.356 --> 26:38.198
And then he typed the letter, Dear Dick and Jane.

26:38.667 --> 26:53.703
I haven't written to thank Jane for the swell typing, for the swell typing job, because I've been waiting until I can send the, i.e., the holograph.

26:54.143 --> 26:55.445
Apparently he's just learning this word.

26:55.885 --> 27:03.213
Think of old Ham having written holographs all these years and not knowing it.

27:03.233 --> 27:07.037
As soon as I definitely get it pared down and in Scribner's hands,

27:07.642 --> 27:09.324
We'll send it over by Harrington.

27:10.085 --> 27:16.573
It was a beautiful job of figuring out what the hell my holograph meant, and I appreciate it very much.

27:17.233 --> 27:23.181
Max Perkins and Dos, that's John Dos Passos, of course, who have read it, like it very much.

27:24.162 --> 27:25.403
No one had seen it at this time.

27:25.503 --> 27:31.571
Jane and Perkins and Dos Passos, his own ones who read it by February 5th of 35.

27:32.372 --> 27:36.957
Dos like it very much, have read it, like it very much, and I'm beginning to feel better about it.

27:37.088 --> 27:46.520
I was so damn pleased that you both liked it, but was afraid maybe Jane liked it because she likes Africa, and that Vic liked it because he likes or liked to drink.

27:47.141 --> 27:53.328
I have cut considerable garden manure and night soil out of it, but have left in the Gulf Stream as you requested.

27:53.869 --> 27:55.251
Question without having to read the whole thing.

27:55.271 --> 27:56.492
Yes, I'm not going to read it anymore.

27:56.512 --> 27:56.612
Okay.

27:57.233 --> 27:59.696
Any chance of getting a zero-art for this?

27:59.716 --> 28:00.638
No, I don't want to do that.

28:00.658 --> 28:01.138
Okay.

28:01.158 --> 28:05.003
But basically that's what deals with Green Hills of Africa, that portion.

28:05.422 --> 28:18.055
And, you know, she, in her letter, said, leave in the stuff about the Gulf Stream, so he quite magnanimously, and maybe incorrectly, but just as a compliment there, says, I left in the stuff about the Gulf Stream as you requested.

28:18.296 --> 28:19.016
As you requested.

28:19.216 --> 28:20.378
Right.

28:20.398 --> 28:20.538
Yeah.

28:20.558 --> 28:20.858
That's great.

28:20.898 --> 28:21.499
How did he sign it?

28:22.900 --> 28:23.821
Ernest.

28:23.841 --> 28:26.004
And you're welcome to read it, you know, later.

28:26.164 --> 28:26.804
Okay.

28:26.844 --> 28:30.228
Regards to... Manuolo.

28:30.408 --> 28:31.790
Yeah.

28:31.810 --> 28:33.171
And then there's some pencil.

28:33.331 --> 28:33.932
Right.

28:34.032 --> 28:34.973
Later in the letter...

28:35.324 --> 28:54.423
He asks Richard to, this is also significant because it's another literary thing, he asks Richard to get Carlos Guterres, who was the mate on the Pilar, to get some baits and tie some baits because he has to do this big snot of a book for Derrido Press.

28:56.184 --> 29:01.710
So obviously that occurred, and Richard, who was a photojournalist, he wanted him to take pictures.

29:03.271 --> 29:04.032
So here we have it.

29:04.518 --> 29:17.770
That paragraph led to Richard Armstrong getting Carlos Gutierrez and trying to Bates, just as Ernest directs in that letter.

29:21.713 --> 29:26.137
And I'll show you those very pictures that that paragraph was the instigation for.

29:26.198 --> 29:28.640
Right here.

29:28.660 --> 29:30.802
And this is Carlos Gutierrez, his mate on the phone.

29:30.822 --> 29:32.023
Carlos is going to spell it.

29:32.043 --> 29:34.525
It's Carlos G-U-T.

29:35.787 --> 29:38.731
I-E, I-E, R-R-E-Z.

29:39.071 --> 29:39.952
R-R-E-Z.

29:40.493 --> 29:56.653
And he specifically tells him to have him, you know, tie the bait, the mackerel a certain way, and it's just fascinating, you know, that... So he's got 12 pictures of his bait.

29:58.455 --> 30:04.022
I love that the letter has all of Hemingway's legendary idiosyncrasies with typing.

30:04.306 --> 30:09.452
The raised letters, you know how it says letters are famous, but I'm going to put my pen down there.

30:10.654 --> 30:10.894
Sure.

30:10.914 --> 30:12.836
I saw a couple of raised letters.

30:12.856 --> 30:14.438
It just looks like a Hemingway letter.

30:14.458 --> 30:14.739
Right.

30:14.819 --> 30:16.801
It's better now become very famous because he's even.

30:17.021 --> 30:17.983
Oh, yeah.

30:18.043 --> 30:23.569
Is this the cornerstone of the... Well, this, I've got nine other letters.

30:23.890 --> 30:26.573
Okay, but the significance of that for you is what?

30:26.974 --> 30:28.395
Oh, this whole thing.

30:28.516 --> 30:32.220
Well, you know, the letters, the carbons from Jane and the ones,

30:32.538 --> 30:44.428
They sort of legitimized her possessing the manuscript, because she says, I'm going to send you the manuscript and the two, you know, the carbon and the original.

30:44.789 --> 30:52.776
So she sends them to him, presumably, and then he sends back to her the original manuscript, the handwritten manuscript, and this, okay?

30:53.516 --> 30:59.201
And he makes his changes on the copy that he then sends to Max Perkins and Scribner's.

30:59.682 --> 31:01.363
Later, in 1947,

31:02.255 --> 31:13.671
Phyllis, the daughter, who was hard up at the time, sold the handwritten manuscript through Scribner's to the University of Virginia Library, and that's where it is now.

31:15.173 --> 31:18.077
But this stuff all... Well, it validates everything.

31:18.097 --> 31:18.878
Yeah, right, exactly.

31:19.199 --> 31:21.102
It's documentation, shall we say.

31:21.122 --> 31:21.843
Right, yeah.

31:21.883 --> 31:23.044
It validates everything else.

31:23.425 --> 31:24.306
Right.

31:24.406 --> 31:28.532
It basically legitimizes the provenance.

31:30.588 --> 31:31.429
Okay.

31:31.449 --> 31:32.350
Okay, that's great.

31:32.931 --> 31:42.445
Would you say that the Times claimed that you have the finest collection of Hemingway manuscript material in private hands, is that correct?

31:42.465 --> 31:51.337
Well, I don't know of any other Hemingway novels, non-fiction novels, any typescripts in a private collection.

31:51.357 --> 31:51.978
I don't know of any.

31:51.998 --> 31:57.546
There may be some, but I don't know of any, and no collector I've talked to knows of any.

31:57.566 --> 32:00.510
All of the Hemingway manuscripts, the University of Texas has some,

32:00.997 --> 32:05.242
Virginia has some, the Kennedy has a number, but I don't know of any in private hands.

32:06.163 --> 32:10.369
And the number of short stories in private hands are very, very few.

32:10.389 --> 32:12.311
There are some, but look at that.

32:12.331 --> 32:12.792
Did you read that?

32:12.812 --> 32:13.593
I had the case made.

32:13.993 --> 32:16.096
It's very beautiful.

32:16.256 --> 32:17.518
Can you describe it for us?

32:18.299 --> 32:22.984
Describe it for the... Yeah, the case is a slip case with a cover.

32:25.367 --> 32:28.371
The story, the capital of the world, the story is about...

32:29.093 --> 32:32.699
A guy who works in a restaurant, a waiter, who wants to be a bullfighter.

32:33.441 --> 32:37.548
And so he picks up a chair and ties a sword to it.

32:37.948 --> 32:43.438
And eventually, in trying to get this other guy who's working with him, he gets stabbed.

32:43.458 --> 32:44.460
That's the plot of the story.

32:44.961 --> 32:54.477
So in some kind of brass welding, soldering, someone has drawn a chair with a sword tied to it.

32:55.216 --> 33:06.610
and then a facsimile awareness having a signature on the front of the box that I had made for.

33:06.691 --> 33:13.179
Prior to the acquisition of this, we could say that you had an excellent collection of first editions.

33:13.199 --> 33:18.085
Yeah, a wonderful collection of first editions, some letters, but nothing like this.

33:18.125 --> 33:24.413
You were what could be regarded as a possessor of a really fine,

33:24.882 --> 33:25.963
Hemingway collection.

33:25.983 --> 33:26.103
Right.

33:26.183 --> 33:27.845
I had all the first editions in Dust Jack.

33:27.865 --> 33:30.908
But nothing that would attract a writer from Boston to come and see you, right?

33:30.928 --> 33:31.889
That's right.

33:31.949 --> 33:33.291
That's for sure.

33:33.671 --> 33:35.753
But no, there's a point here.

33:35.793 --> 33:39.437
So tell me about opportunity and now what happened?

33:39.457 --> 33:44.843
I mean, now you're, did this occasion you're becoming a dealer in rare books?

33:44.863 --> 33:49.708
No, I made the commitment to become a dealer before, but, you know, having had all of the time,

33:50.093 --> 33:54.459
as a serious collector, you know, I know what this stuff is, and you haven't seen it yet.

33:54.559 --> 34:00.628
You haven't seen it all yet, and I'll continue to show it to you, but, you know, just the wealth of material was just phenomenal.

34:00.648 --> 34:03.392
And just let me briefly show you some more of this stuff.

34:03.412 --> 34:05.695
You've seen the Cosmopolitan article.

34:07.338 --> 34:13.326
This is just a first edition one of 300 things that had a nice box before.

34:13.647 --> 34:20.016
This is the, it's hard to call it a short story,

34:20.823 --> 34:26.330
But it's... Today is Friday.

34:26.690 --> 34:27.772
It's A5A.

34:28.212 --> 34:29.854
I love the story.

34:29.954 --> 34:31.636
Yeah.

34:31.656 --> 34:33.078
And this is the first edition of that.

34:33.579 --> 34:36.743
This was one of the six magazine articles that I got.

34:38.425 --> 34:40.007
Well, well, well, Ernest Hemingway.

34:41.208 --> 34:44.552
Bullfighting, sport and industry.

34:44.572 --> 34:47.275
Page 83 of Fortune magazine from March 1930.

34:47.315 --> 34:49.378
This is the second issue of Fortune magazine.

34:49.645 --> 34:55.594
This was a precursor to death in the afternoon, and it's never been reprinted.

34:56.415 --> 35:05.549
I have permission from the Hemingway family, the lawyers, in writing, to put out a small press edition of this, and I will do that in the next year or so.

35:05.649 --> 35:07.031
I would like an opportunity to buy one.

35:07.051 --> 35:07.311
Sure.

35:07.632 --> 35:08.333
Right.

35:08.353 --> 35:08.633
Okay.

35:08.653 --> 35:09.635
All right.

35:09.655 --> 35:10.656
Yeah.

35:10.676 --> 35:12.339
No, because we have a small Hemingway family.

35:12.359 --> 35:12.559
Right.

35:12.579 --> 35:13.961
Well, this will be an A item.

35:13.981 --> 35:14.081
Yeah.

35:14.101 --> 35:14.783
You're going to sell them?

35:15.263 --> 35:15.464
Right.

35:15.524 --> 35:16.525
I want to buy one.

35:16.545 --> 35:16.725
Sure.

35:16.826 --> 35:17.226
You bet.

35:17.246 --> 35:18.268
All right.

35:18.288 --> 35:18.488
All right.

35:18.670 --> 35:45.724
but very few things have not been republished you know but i was aware this one wasn't and i was you know just sort of parenthetically i'll tell you a quick story i was retained a movie producer read the l.a times article on this acquisition and he called me and said he'd like to to do a movie of green hills of africa and i said well of course you know i do have a type script but the rights for movie don't go with that well

35:46.109 --> 35:48.132
Yeah, but then I started talking.

35:48.152 --> 35:53.580
But I am a lawyer, and I do know the lawyer for the Hemingway family.

35:53.600 --> 35:54.661
Whose name is?

35:54.681 --> 36:04.115
His name is Bobrinsky, B-O-B-R-I-N-S-K-Y, in Chicago.

36:05.016 --> 36:07.680
And I talked to him before, just once before.

36:07.700 --> 36:15.812
So the producer retained me to attempt to acquire the rights to make a motion picture production of Greenhouse of Africa.

36:16.602 --> 36:18.244
So that was one offshoot.

36:18.264 --> 36:21.249
That didn't work out, but it was fun doing it.

36:22.791 --> 36:25.976
And that was because of the publicity for this stuff.

36:25.996 --> 36:27.578
This came again with that collection.

36:28.179 --> 36:30.443
This is one of the first six things I got from this song.

36:30.643 --> 36:34.549
This, and this, and then this.

36:34.569 --> 36:36.472
And this later I got from the daughter.

36:36.792 --> 36:40.057
And these letters, which are really the most magnificent.

36:40.077 --> 36:43.302
This is awfully nice.

36:43.687 --> 36:45.910
I mean, I'll never find anything like this again.

36:45.930 --> 36:47.051
That's a cartoon or a dealer.

36:47.071 --> 36:49.073
