But nationally, I didn't want that to happen.

55:12.902 --> 55:14.023
I didn't want any competition.

55:14.524 --> 55:18.828
But, you know, for this eight-month period, she could have contacted anyone she wanted.

55:18.848 --> 55:20.250
In any case, we get down there.

55:20.390 --> 55:22.712
We meet at the conference room of her bank.

55:22.732 --> 55:23.413
She's not there.

55:24.372 --> 55:27.355
The people at the Met told me, she's over-xeroxing the stuff.

55:27.375 --> 55:28.636
And that was the first good sign.

55:28.656 --> 55:31.999
If she's xeroxing the stuff, she's going to sell it to me.

55:32.019 --> 55:32.980
So then she got there.

55:33.200 --> 55:36.283
And she was really courteous, a really nice woman.

55:36.303 --> 55:37.624
And the press was there.

55:37.665 --> 55:40.567
They took some pictures of her holding up some of the stuff.

55:40.948 --> 55:42.149
And wanted to interview me.

55:42.169 --> 55:44.391
I said, your feeling must be, oh, please.

55:44.471 --> 55:45.252
Exactly.

55:45.272 --> 55:45.652
Exactly.

55:45.672 --> 55:46.193
You got it.

55:47.334 --> 55:48.835
Basically, it was, get out.

55:48.855 --> 55:49.596
Let's do this deal.

55:49.616 --> 55:51.718
If I get the stuff, I'd be happy to talk to you.

55:51.738 --> 55:52.919
Right now, you're a distraction.

55:53.059 --> 55:54.160
Oh, a major distraction.

55:54.410 --> 55:57.435
And so they took the pictures and then left.

55:57.455 --> 55:58.917
No, this was local press, Florida press?

55:58.937 --> 55:59.858
This is local press.

56:00.259 --> 56:03.444
Have you got any copies of these stories, by the way, Seth?

56:04.766 --> 56:08.732
I've got some stuff over there, some public stuff that I'll give you.

56:08.792 --> 56:08.992
Good.

56:10.935 --> 56:11.416
So, go ahead.

56:11.436 --> 56:11.696
Excuse me.

56:11.716 --> 56:19.388
Anyway, so then Lynn and I and the book dealer sat down in the room, and I made another offer, which was more than any figure that had ever been mentioned before.

56:20.689 --> 56:22.392
And she accepted it.

56:23.131 --> 56:24.913
So we're all happy.

56:24.933 --> 56:27.116
Not until the check is signed in the papers.

56:27.136 --> 56:29.419
Did you have any kind of contract?

56:29.439 --> 56:31.862
Well, yeah, we made a very brief contract, basically.

56:32.443 --> 56:38.210
You know, what the stuff was, and then I was buying it, and we also signed the book dealer, Lynn, and myself.

56:38.491 --> 56:44.138
And how did you get to be, own the rights to that unpublished, that piece over there that you showed me?

56:45.860 --> 56:48.423
That unpublished, the Fortune magazine piece?

56:48.443 --> 56:51.467
I talked to the book, I talked to the Hemingway lawyer once before.

56:51.785 --> 57:04.943
And then the movie producer, the guy who produced the Presidio with Sean Connery, and earlier he was, I think, the producer or co-producer of Breathless with Richard Gare a few years earlier.

57:04.963 --> 57:08.267
But, you know, a serious producer in Hollywood.

57:09.769 --> 57:20.323
So I'm talking to Bob Brinsky about this, one of our conversations, and I mentioned that I'm aware of some unpublished Hemingway items, and I intend to be a small press publisher.

57:20.607 --> 57:25.912
So I start talking about this, and ask him directly, and then write him a letter, and he writes me a letterbox.

57:26.252 --> 57:27.113
That's pretty nice.

57:28.074 --> 57:29.495
You don't have to pay him anything?

57:29.515 --> 57:33.699
Yeah, you wanted me to make a donation to the Hemingway Foundation.

57:34.340 --> 57:36.502
That's really very decent.

57:36.642 --> 57:39.064
Oh, it certainly is, yeah.

57:40.506 --> 57:41.066
That's great.

57:41.887 --> 57:42.788
That's a good story.

57:43.969 --> 57:49.534
One thing we haven't really addressed is why

57:49.784 --> 57:52.046
I noticed you've got some Walker Percy books up there.

57:52.086 --> 57:56.311
You have a William Styron, Mario Puzo, but these are books for stock, right?

57:56.671 --> 57:56.832
Yeah.

57:56.872 --> 57:59.815
These are books that you sell, Ken Kesey, London.

57:59.895 --> 58:00.255
Whatever.

58:00.856 --> 58:02.418
But you really only collect Hemingway.

58:03.559 --> 58:04.360
Yeah.

58:04.640 --> 58:07.423
Well, Larry McMurtry, I'm pretty interested in.

58:07.443 --> 58:08.604
And I like mystery writers, too.

58:09.245 --> 58:10.266
You collect?

58:10.286 --> 58:11.988
Well, I wouldn't say collect really now.

58:12.248 --> 58:15.752
I mean, I have most of the stuff, but mostly it's really part of an inventory.

58:16.693 --> 58:19.656
Tell me why the passion for Hemingway.

58:22.775 --> 58:37.976
I guess I can sort of obliquely, I've read the first chapter, first two chapters to Afraid of World Arms a couple hundred times, and it's like music to me.

58:37.996 --> 58:39.939
I mean, it's just beautiful.

58:40.399 --> 58:44.425
It's like when you listen to some great music and you have a real emotional response to it.

58:44.846 --> 58:48.350
You know, some of Hemingway, I react that way too.

58:48.491 --> 58:50.233
And then...

58:50.770 --> 58:59.844
I don't know all the emotions that go into being a collector, but once you start, I think it's the hunt, really.

59:00.225 --> 59:04.031
Possessing the stuff isn't that great, but it's the fun of the hunt.

59:04.071 --> 59:17.892
That's why I decided to go into the business and virtually put all of the stuff for sale, because the hunt was fun, but once you have everything, then it's not that fun anymore, because so seldom do you find something you don't have.

59:18.901 --> 59:25.768
I guess, obviously, the culmination to my collecting was finding this one magnificent person.

59:25.809 --> 59:27.330
How old are you?

59:27.350 --> 59:27.550
49.

59:27.570 --> 59:29.012
49.

59:29.312 --> 59:33.877
But you would say that that's a young man, is the reason I ask.

59:35.559 --> 59:41.085
You could collect for 25 more years, but do you think that you'll find an experience as great as this?

59:41.606 --> 59:42.427
No, I don't think so.

59:42.447 --> 59:43.368
I can't imagine.

59:44.869 --> 59:48.233
I can't imagine there being, there existing, a closet full of

59:48.365 --> 59:50.949
of original Hemingway material, and they're made.

59:51.229 --> 59:53.192
Well, they're at the Hemingway, but that's my point.

59:53.212 --> 59:54.193
You just collect Hemingway.

59:54.233 --> 59:58.499
You might find the Larry McMurtry thing someplace, but that doesn't, this is the kick.

59:58.779 --> 59:59.801
Yeah, right.

01:00:00.081 --> 01:00:04.507
And now I sense it's all for sale, technically.

01:00:04.567 --> 01:00:05.088
Is that correct?

01:00:05.248 --> 01:00:05.549
Sure.

01:00:05.629 --> 01:00:06.410
The price is right?

01:00:06.670 --> 01:00:09.855
Well, right, but I haven't, you know, I've had it for two, two and a half years.

01:00:09.895 --> 01:00:16.884
I haven't carefully cataloged it and described it and advertised it and, you know, I haven't really tried to sell it.

01:00:16.904 --> 01:00:17.325
I mean, it's,

01:00:17.609 --> 01:00:45.473
eminently saleable material let's say a guy like maury neville walks in yeah and says right um here's the check i've signed it you and he has the means to do something like yes he does and he's a very careful collector he's been a book dealer for a lot of years so he tends to want to buy things wholesale so the truth is i probably wouldn't sell it to maury but there's some retail customers out there who would be a better market and if i wanted to you know once i

01:00:45.925 --> 01:00:56.681
get into selling it, then it's something that I'll make a description of and give descriptions to four or five people who have wonderful collections and the means to buy it.

01:00:57.322 --> 01:00:59.766
So you expect at some point, realistically, to sell it.

01:00:59.786 --> 01:01:01.508
Yeah.

01:01:01.528 --> 01:01:02.410
You're going to enjoy it.

01:01:02.971 --> 01:01:03.271
Right.

01:01:03.391 --> 01:01:05.494
In the meantime, I'm not terribly anxious to do that.

01:01:05.514 --> 01:01:06.576
That's a nice story.

01:01:07.117 --> 01:01:09.881
It's a good story for us.

01:01:09.961 --> 01:01:14.548
And it's a good story because it does illustrate that for you, the excitement was really in the hunt.

01:01:14.782 --> 01:01:19.729
The anxiety that JFK could be breathing down your neck, for instance.

01:01:20.111 --> 01:01:21.518
Or Maury Neville could be...

